Insurance problem in Developing Countries
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
A key feature of insurance is protection of risk-averse individuals who
 might be adversely affected by external phenomena.
 By pooling individual risks, insurance leads to Pareto-preferred states
 - enabling individuals to engage in risky activities which they otherwise
 won't.
 With risk of natural calamities and underdeveloped support as well as low-per
 capita income, developing countries are make a good case for insurance
 - more so if we consider that a labour-intensive agricultural sector is
 the primary sector of production in the developing countries.
 Still, it is often found that the costs and extent of administration in
 developing countries provide special challenges to provision of individual
 insurance.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
It is observed that risk-aversion due leads to suboptimal selection for
 farmers in the developing world.
 This is observed in form of sharecropping or selection of low-risk crops.
 Rosenzweig and Binswanger
