Moral Hazard
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
Moral hazard arises when customers do something that sellers don't know
 of.
 There is the possibility that the occurrence of some insurable event can
 be influenced by the unobservable actions of the individual.
 This incentive can be modeled.
 There is a clear problem is a farmer/participant doesn't want to put a
 lot of effort is s/he sees a certain income is guaranteed as the lower
 output performer (free-riding on high-output farmers).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
If high efforts are with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

 and no efforts with 
\begin_inset Formula $q$
\end_inset

, then expected utility with high efforts is 
\begin_inset Formula $pU(H)+(1-p)U(L)-c$
\end_inset

 while no efforts yield 
\begin_inset Formula $qU(H)+(1-q)U(L)$
\end_inset

.
 Without insurance, the farmer puts extra effort if 
\begin_inset Formula $pU(H)+(1-p)U(L)-c>qU(H)+(1-q)U(L)$
\end_inset

.
 With insurance, if farmers with H pool their harvests and with L receive
 a compensation, then we have 
\begin_inset Formula $pH+(1-p)L$
\end_inset

 assured for every farmer and since, 
\begin_inset Formula $U(pH+(1-p)L)>pU(H)+(1-p)U(L)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\size footnotesize
The question that one may ask is how much insurance can be offered without
 worsening incentives? If perfect insurance conditions fails to hold we
 consider the second best-alternative.
 
\begin_inset Formula $pX+(1-p)Y=pH+(1-p)L$
\end_inset

 for farmer's output 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

